      <scopecontent id="aspace_f4465b647995fcd259937681622fd4de">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>Collection of 51 letters sent to Rodney Mason from his brother Edwin Cooley Mason and mother Minerva Needham Mason, 1875-1878. The letters were sent as the pair travelled from Newport Barracks, Kentucky; Columbus Barracks, Ohio; Fort Vancouver, Washington; and Portland, Oregon, and document the Edwin Cooley Mason's service in the 21st Infantry Regiment of the Department of Columbia.</p>
         <p>A majority of the letters relate to the Nez Perce War and the Bannock War and mention generals Oliver Otis Howard and Nelson Miles among others, as well as Indigenous peoples including the Nez Percé (also known as nimíipuu), Bannock, Coeur d'Alene (also known as Skitswish), Okanagan (also known as Syilx, Okanogan, or Okinagan), Paloos (also known as Palouse), and Yakama.</p>
         <p>Letters dated 1877 chronicle the military service of Edwin Cooley Mason in Idaho, moving from Lapwai to Cow Island before returning to Fort Vancouver. These include mention of Chief Joseph (born Hin-mah-too-yah-lat-kekt), leader of the Wallowa (wal-lam-wat-kain) band of the Nez Perce Tribe, and others taken prisoner by Nelson Miles. A letter dated 1878 indicates the beginning of the Bannock War and references Chief Moses (born Kwiltalahun, later called Sulk-stalk-scosum), leader of the Sinkiuse-Columbia.</p>
      </scopecontent>
